# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: blender-3d
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] In 3D computer graphics, **3D modeling** is the process of developing a mathematical coordinate-based representation of a surface of an object (inanimate or living) in three dimensions via specialized software by manipulating edges, vertices, and polygons in a simulated 3D space.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Three-dimensional (3D) models represent a physical body using a collection of points in 3D space, connected by various geometric entities such as triangles, lines, curved surfaces, etc.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Being a collection of data (points and other information), 3D models can be created manually, algorithmically (procedural modeling), or by scanning.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Their surfaces may be further defined with texture mapping.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] The product is called a 3D model, while someone who works with 3D models may be referred to as a 3D artist or a 3D modeler.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] A 3D model can also be displayed as a two-dimensional image through a process called 3D rendering or used in a computer simulation of physical phenomena.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] 3D models may be created automatically or manually.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] The 3D model can be physically created using 3D printing devices that form 2D layers of the model with three-dimensional material, one layer at a time.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Without a 3D model, a 3D print is not possible.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] 3D modeling software is a class of 3D computer graphics software used to produce 3D models.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Individual programs of this class are called modeling applications.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] 3D models are now widely used anywhere in 3D graphics and CAD but their history predates the widespread use of 3D graphics on personal computers.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] In the past, many computer games used pre-rendered images of 3D models as sprites before computers could render them in real-time.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] The designer can then see the model in various directions and views, this can help the designer see if the object is created as intended to compared to their original vision.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Seeing the design this way can help the designer or company figure out changes or improvements needed to the product.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Simple wireframes were the first versions of early 3D models, which were mainly used to view construction plans and mechanical parts.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Better graphics hardware and software allowed for the creation of solid and surface models in the 1970s and 1980s, giving designers a more realistic and clear representation of physical objects.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] By the 1990s, parametric modeling became popular, letting designers change a model by changing its basic parameters instead of redrawing it from scratch.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Thanks to virtual reality, artificial intelligence and generative design tools, 3D modeling today goes past engineering and is influencing fields like animation, gaming, product design and cinema.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Solid and shell modeling can create functionally identical objects.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Differences between them are mostly variations in the way they are created and edited and conventions of use in various fields and differences in types of approximations between the model and reality.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Shell models must be manifold (having no holes or cracks in the shell) to be meaningful as a real object.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] For example, in a shell model of a cube, all six sides must be connected with no gaps in the edges or the corners.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Polygonal meshes (and to a lesser extent, subdivision surfaces) are by far the most common representation.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Level sets are a useful representation for deforming surfaces that undergo many topological changes, such as fluids.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] The process of transforming representations of objects, such as the middle point coordinate of a sphere and a point on its circumference, into a polygon representation of a sphere is called tessellation.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] This step is used in polygon-based rendering, where objects are broken down from abstract representations ("primitives") such as spheres, cones etc., to so-called *meshes*, which are nets of interconnected triangles.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Meshes of triangles (instead of e.g., squares) are popular as they have proven to be easy to rasterize (the surface described by each triangle is planar, so the projection is always convex).
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Polygon representations are not used in all rendering techniques, and in these cases the tessellation step is not included in the transition from abstract representation to rendered scene.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] The modeling stage consists of shaping individual objects that are later used in the scene.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] In some cases, there is no strict distinction between these phases; in such cases, modeling is just part of the scene creation process (this is the case, for example, with Caligari trueSpace and Realsoft 3D).
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] 3D models can also be created using the technique of Photogrammetry with dedicated programs such as RealityCapture, Metashape and 3DF Zephyr.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Cleanup and further processing can be performed with applications such as MeshLab, the GigaMesh Software Framework, netfabb or MeshMixer.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Photogrammetry creates models using algorithms to interpret the shape and texture of real-world objects and environments based on photographs taken from many angles of the subject.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Complex materials such as blowing sand, clouds, and liquid sprays are modeled with particle systems, and are a mass of 3D coordinates which have either points, polygons, texture splats or sprites assigned to them.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] There are a variety of 3D modeling programs that can be used in the industries of engineering, interior design, film and others.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Each 3D modeling software has specific capabilities and can be utilized to fulfill demands for the industry.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Many programs include export options to form a g-code, applicable to additive or subtractive manufacturing machinery.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] G-code (computer numerical control) works with automated technology to form a real-world rendition of 3D models.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] This code is a specific set of instructions to carry out steps of a product's manufacturing.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] The first widely available commercial application of human virtual models appeared in 1998 on the Lands' End web site.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] The human virtual models were created by the company My Virtual Mode Inc. and enabled users to create a model of themselves and try on 3D clothing.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] There are several modern programs that allow for the creation of virtual human models (Poser being one example).
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] The development of cloth simulation software such as Marvelous Designer, CLO3D and Optitex, has enabled artists and fashion designers to model dynamic 3D clothing on the computer.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Dynamic 3D clothing is used for virtual fashion catalogs, as well as for dressing 3D characters for video games, 3D animation movies, for digital doubles in movies, as a creation tool for digital fashion brands, as well as for making clothes for avatars in virtual worlds such as SecondLife.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] 3D photorealistic effects are often achieved without wire-frame modeling and are sometimes indistinguishable in the final form.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Some graphic art software includes filters that can be applied to 2D vector graphics or 2D raster graphics on transparent layers.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Disadvantages compared to 2D photorealistic rendering may include a software learning curve and difficulty achieving certain photorealistic effects.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Some photorealistic effects may be achieved with special rendering filters included in the 3D modeling software.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] For the best of both worlds, some artists use a combination of 3D modeling followed by editing the 2D computer-rendered images from the 3D model.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] A large market for 3D models (as well as 3D-related content, such as textures, scripts, etc.) exists—either for individual models or large collections.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Several online marketplaces for 3D content allow individual artists to sell content that they have created, including TurboSquid, MyMiniFactory,Patreon,Sketchfab, CGTrader, and Cults.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Often, the artists' goal is to get additional value out of assets they have previously created for projects.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] By doing so, artists can earn more money out of their old content, and companies can save money by buying pre-made models instead of paying an employee to create one from scratch.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] These marketplaces typically split the sale between themselves and the artist that created the asset, artists get 40% to 95% of the sales according to the marketplace.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] In most cases, the artist retains ownership of the 3D model while the customer only buys the right to use and present the model.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Some artists sell their products directly in their own stores, offering their products at a lower price by not using intermediaries.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] The architecture, engineering and construction (AEC) industry is the biggest market for 3D modeling, with an estimated value of $12.13 billion by 2028.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] This is due to the increasing adoption of 3D modeling in the AEC industry, which helps to improve design accuracy, reduce errors and omissions and facilitate collaboration among project stakeholders.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Over the last several years numerous marketplaces specializing in 3D rendering and printing models have emerged.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Some of the 3D printing marketplaces are a combination of models sharing sites, with or without a built in e-com capability.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Some of those platforms also offer 3D printing services on demand, software for model rendering and dynamic viewing of items.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] The term 3D printing or three-dimensional printing is a form of additive manufacturing technology where a three-dimensional object is created from successive layers of material.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Objects can be created without the need for complex and expensive molds or assembly of multiple parts.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] 3D printing allows ideas to be prototyped and tested without having to go through a more time-consuming production process.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] 3D models can be purchased from online markets and printed by individuals or companies using commercially available 3D printers, enabling the home-production of objects such as spare parts and even medical equipment.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Open-source tools (for instance Blender, FreeCAD, MeshLab, OpenSCAD) coexist with commercial packages (some examples are: Autodesk Maya/3ds Max/Fusion 360, SolidWorks, CATIA, Cinema 4D, ZBrush, Rhino, Houdini, SketchUp, CLO 3D/Marvelous Designer, Revit, Archicad).
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] The RDF representation of 3D models can be used in reasoning, which enables intelligent 3D applications which, for example, can automatically compare two 3D models by volume.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Overall, these examples are an illustration of 3D modelling being a tool of general purpose representational layer that creates a bridge between sensing to analysis, design, communication and fabrication.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Despite 3D modelling being widely adopted in various domains, several constraints shape how the technology is utilized.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Access and cost remain an issue in many regions of the world.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Commercial licences, training, and capable hardware can be difficult to find in select regions.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] It can also be out of reach for students and small studios that cannot afford it.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Open-source ecosystems and school programs can aid in making this less of an issue, but availability and support are uneven which in turn creates an equity gap in who can learn and apply 3D modelling.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Workflow complexity is another limitation.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] To practice 3D modelling effectively it requires knowledge of many different things.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] A 3D modelling specialist needs to understand topology, UV mapping, rigging, simulation and rendering for DCC.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] For CAD/CAM modelling parametric constraints, tolerances and manufacturing constraints must be known by the developer.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Information schema and coordination are both required for BIM.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Moving assets between tools can introduce incompatibility issues (meshes vs.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] NURBS/solids/parametric features; unit scaling; normals; material definitions), and format conversions may cause data loss without careful management.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] At scale, energy consumption can be large (this is due to high resolution simulations and rendering and dense 3D scans), which directs teams to try and optimize design complexity and adopting more efficient pipelines.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] In research and heritage work, there is another constraint where ethical and policy questions include provenance, licensing and representation (how “authoritative” a reconstruction should be labelled), especially as these reconstruction are utilized for public communication and educational purposes.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Finally, classroom and outreach deployments must take into account pedagogical support: learners need step by step guidance and clear examples and models to follow.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Without this, the tool’s complexity will be more of a barrier that slows students down instead of enabling them to understand and be creative.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] In 3D modeling, simulations are digital processes that copy how things behave in the real world, in a virtual space.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] Without creating actual prototypes, it lets designers and animators test how objects move, interact, or react to forces.
[src:blender-3d/3d-modeling] By recreating processes such as collisions, fluid movement, fabric draping, or particle motion, simulations help increase design accuracy, enhance visual effects, and save both time and materials.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender was used to produce the Academy Award-winning film *Flow* (2024).
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender was initially developed as an in-house application by the Dutch animation studio NeoGeo (no relation to the video game brand), and was officially launched on January 2, 1994.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Version 1.00 was released in January 1995, with the primary author being the company co-owner and software developer Ton Roosendaal.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The name *Blender* was inspired by a song by the Swiss electronic band Yello, from the album *Baby*, which NeoGeo used in its showreel.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Some design choices and experiences for Blender were carried over from an earlier 3D ray-tracing software application, called Traces, that Roosendaal developed for NeoGeo on the Commodore Amiga platform during the 1987–1991 period.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] On January 1, 1998, Blender was released publicly online as SGI freeware.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] NeoGeo was later dissolved, and its client contracts were taken over by another company.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] After NeoGeo's dissolution, Ton Roosendaal founded Not a Number Technologies (NaN, a reference to the computing term of the same name) in June 1998 to further develop Blender, initially distributing it as shareware until NaN went bankrupt in 2002.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] This also resulted in the discontinuation of Blender's development.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] In May 2002, Roosendaal started the non-profit Blender Foundation, with the first goal to find a way to continue developing and promoting Blender as a community-based open-source project.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] On July 18, 2002, Roosendaal started the "Free Blender" campaign, a crowdfunding precursor.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The campaign aimed at open-sourcing Blender for a one-time payment of €100,000 (USD 100,670 at the time), with the money being collected from the community.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] On September 7, 2002, it was announced that they had collected enough funds and would release the Blender source code.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Today, Blender is free and open-source software, largely developed by its community as well as 26 full-time employees and 12 freelancers employed by the Blender Institute.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The Blender Foundation initially reserved the right to use dual licensing so that, in addition to GPL 2.0-or-later, Blender would have been available also under the "Blender License", which did not require disclosing source code but required payments to the Blender Foundation.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] However, this option was never exercised and was suspended indefinitely in 2005.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender is solely available under "GNU GPLv2 or any later" and was not updated to the GPLv3, as "no evident benefits" were seen.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The binary releases of Blender are under GNU GPLv3 or later because of the incorporated Apache libraries.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] In 2019, with the release of version 2.80, the integrated game engine for making and prototyping video games was removed; Blender's developers recommended that users migrate to more powerful open source game engines such as Godot instead.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] In February 2002, the fate of the Blender software company, NaN, became evident as it faced imminent closure in March.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Nevertheless, one more release was pushed out, Blender 2.25.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] As a sort of Easter egg and last personal tag, the artists and developers decided to add a 3D model of a chimpanzee head (called a "monkey" in the software).
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It was created by Willem-Paul van Overbruggen (SLiD3), who named it Suzanne after the orangutan in the Kevin Smith film *Jay and Silent Bob Strike Back*.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Suzanne is Blender's alternative to more common test models such as the Utah Teapot and the Stanford Bunny.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] A low-polygon model with only 500 faces, Suzanne is included in Blender and often used as a quick and easy way to test materials, animations, rigs, textures, and lighting setups.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It is included as a primitive, alongside other meshes such as cubes and planes.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The largest Blender contest gives out an award called the **Suzanne Award**.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender has support for a variety of geometric primitives, including polygon meshes, Bézier curves, NURBS surfaces, metaballs, icospheres, text, and an n-gon modeling system called B-mesh.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] There is also an advanced polygonal modelling system which can be accessed through an edit mode.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It supports features such as extrusion, bevelling, and subdividing.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Modifiers apply various non-destructive effects which can be applied upon rendering or exporting, such as subdivision surfaces.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] These effects are sorted into categories such as generate and deform.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] A few examples of commonly used modifiers are generally subdivide surface, geometry nodes, solidify, and shrinkwrap.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender has multi-resolution digital sculpting, which includes dynamic topology, "baking", remeshing, re-symmetrization, and decimation.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The latter is used to simplify models for exporting purposes (an example being game assets).
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender has a node graph system for procedurally and non-destructively creating and manipulating geometry.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It was first added to Blender 2.92, which focuses on object scattering and instancing.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It takes the form of a modifier, so it can be stacked over other different modifiers.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The system uses object attributes, which can be modified and overridden with string inputs.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Attributes can include positions, normals and UV maps.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] All attributes can be viewed in an attribute spreadsheet editor.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The Geometry Nodes utility also has the capability of creating primitive meshes.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] In Blender 3.0, support for creating and modifying curves objects was added to Geometry Nodes; in the same release, the Geometry Nodes workflow was completely redesigned with fields, in order to make the system more intuitive and work like shader nodes.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender can be used to simulate smoke, rain, dust, cloth, fluids, hair, and rigid bodies.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The fluid simulator can be used for simulating liquids, like water being poured into a cup.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It uses Lattice Boltzmann methods (LBM) to simulate fluids and allows for plenty of adjustment of particles and resolution.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The particle physics fluid simulation creates particles that follow the smoothed-particle hydrodynamics method.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] In Blender 2.82, a new fluid simulation system called Mantaflow was added, replacing the old FLIP system.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] In Blender 2.92, another fluid simulation system called APIC, which builds on Mantaflow, was added.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Vortices and more stable calculations are improved from the FLIP system.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Cloth simulation is done by simulating vertices with a rigid body simulation.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] If done on a 3D mesh, it will produce similar effects as the soft body simulation.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender's keyframed animation capabilities include inverse kinematics, armatures, hooks, curve- and lattice-based deformations, shape keys, non-linear animation, constraints, and vertex weighting.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] In addition, its Grease Pencil tools allow for 2D animation within a full 3D pipeline.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender includes three render engines since version 2.80: EEVEE, Workbench and Cycles.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It supports rendering through both the CPU and the GPU.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Cycles supports the Open Shading Language since Blender 2.65.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Cycles Hybrid Rendering is possible in Version 2.92 with OptiX.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Tiles are calculated with GPU in combination with CPU.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] EEVEE is a new physically based real-time renderer.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] While it is capable of driving Blender's real-time viewport for creating assets thanks to its speed, it can also work as a renderer for final frames.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Workbench is a real-time render engine designed for fast rendering during modelling and animation preview.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Workbench supports assigning colors to objects for visual distinction.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Cycles is a path-tracing render engine that is designed to be interactive and easy to use, while still supporting many features.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It has been included with Blender since 2011, with the release of Blender 2.61.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Cycles supports the Advanced Vector Extensions, AVX2 and AVX-512 extension sets, as well as CPU acceleration in modern hardware.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Hydra Storm is a real-time leveraged rendering engine by Pixar made to keep a consistent look between render engines.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It was added in Blender 4.0 and is faster than EEVEE and Cycles for simple scenes, while compromising on quality.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It is an addon and must be enabled in Preferences.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Cycles supports GPU rendering, which is used to speed up rendering times.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] GPU rendering typically requires compatible graphics drivers installed on the system.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender automatically detects supported GPU devices through these drivers without requiring manual installation of development toolkits in most cases.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Since Version 2.90, this limitation of SLI cards is broken with Nvidia's NVLink.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The integrator is the core rendering algorithm used for lighting computations.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Cycles currently supports a path tracing integrator with direct light sampling.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It works well for a variety of lighting setups, but it is not as suitable for caustics and certain other complex lighting situations.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Rays are traced from the camera into the scene, bouncing around until they find a light source (a lamp, an object material emitting light, or the world background), or until they are simply terminated based on the number of maximum bounces determined in the light path settings for the renderer.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] To find lamps and surfaces emitting light, both indirect light sampling (letting the ray follow the surface bidirectional scattering distribution function, or BSDF) and direct light sampling (picking a light source and tracing a ray towards it) are used.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The default path tracing integrator is a "pure" path tracer.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] This integrator works by sending several light rays that act as photons from the camera out into the scene.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] These rays will eventually hit either: a light source, an object, or the world background.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] If these rays hit an object, they will bounce based on the angle of impact, and continue bouncing until a light source has been reached or until a maximum number of bounces, as determined by the user, which will cause it to terminate and result in a black, unlit pixel.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Multiple rays are calculated and averaged out for each pixel, a process known as "sampling".
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] This sampling number is set by the user and greatly affects the final image.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Lower sampling often results in more noise and has the potential to create "fireflies" (which are uncharacteristically bright pixels), while higher sampling greatly reduces noise, but also increases render times.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The alternative is a branched path tracing integrator, which works mostly the same way.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Branched path tracing splits the light rays at each intersection with an object according to different surface components, and takes all lights into account for shading instead of just one.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] This added complexity makes computing each ray slower but reduces noise in the render, especially in scenes dominated by direct (one-bounce) lighting.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] This was removed in Blender 3.0 with the advent of Cycles X, as improvements to the pure path tracing integrator made the branched path tracing integrator redundant.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] (Note that the shader nodes editor is shown in the image, although mostly correct, has undergone a slight change, changing how the UI is structured and looks).
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Materials define the look of meshes, NURBS curves, and other geometric objects.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] They consist of three shaders to define the mesh's surface appearance, volume inside, and surface displacement.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The *surface shader* defines the light interaction at the surface of the mesh.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] One or more bidirectional scattering distribution functions, or BSDFs, can specify if incoming light is reflected, refracted into the mesh, or absorbed.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The alpha value is one measure of translucency.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] When the surface shader does not reflect or absorb light, it enters the volume (light transmission).
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] If no volume shader is specified, it will pass straight through (or be refracted, see refractive index or IOR) to another side of the mesh.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] If one is defined, a *volume shader* describes the light interaction as it passes through the volume of the mesh.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Light may be scattered, absorbed, or even emitted at any point in the volume.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The shape of the surface may be altered by *displacement shaders*.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] In this way, textures can be used to make the mesh surface more detailed.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Depending on the settings, the displacement may be virtual-only modifying the surface normals to give the impression of displacement (also known as bump mapping) – real, or a combination of real displacement with bump mapping.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] EEVEE (or Eevee) is a real-time PBR renderer included in Blender from version 2.8.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] This render engine was given the nickname EEVEE, after the Pokémon species.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The name was later made into the backronym "Extra Easy Virtual Environment Engine" or EEVEE.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] With the release of Blender 4.2 LTS in July 2024, EEVEE received an overhaul by its lead developer, Clément Foucault, called EEVEE Next.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] EEVEE Next boasts a variety of new features for Blender's real-time and rasterised renderer, including screen-space global illumination (SSGI), virtual shadowmapping, sunlight extraction from HDRIs, and a rewritten system for reflections and indirect lighting via light probe volumes and cube maps.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] EEVEE Next also brings improved volumetric rendering, along with support for *displacement shaders* and an improved depth of field system similar to Cycles.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] As of the Blender 5.0 beta, "EEVEE Next" is to be known simply as "EEVEE".
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Plans for future releases of EEVEE include support for hardware-accelerated ray-tracing and continued improvements to performance and shader compilation.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Using the default 3D viewport drawing system for modeling, texturing, etc.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender allows procedural and node-based textures, as well as texture painting, projective painting, vertex painting, weight painting and dynamic painting.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender has a node-based compositor within the rendering pipeline, which is accelerated with OpenCL, and in 4.0 it supports GPU.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It also includes a non-linear video editor called the Video Sequence Editor (VSE), with support for effects like Gaussian blur, color grading, fade and wipe transitions, and other video transformations.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender supports Python scripting for the creation of custom tools, prototyping, importing/exporting from other formats, and task automation.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] This allows for integration with several external render engines through plugins/addons.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender itself can also be compiled & imported as a Python library for further automation and development.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Additionally, Blender supports many addons and plugins that can make certain tasks easier for users.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The Blender Game Engine was a built-in real-time graphics and logic engine with features such as collision detection, a dynamics engine, and programmable logic.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It also allowed the creation of stand-alone, real-time applications ranging from architectural visualization to video games.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] In April 2018, the engine was removed from the upcoming Blender 2.8 release series, due to updates and revisions to the engine lagging behind other game engines such as Unity and the open-source Godot.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] In the 2.8 announcements, the Blender team specifically mentioned the Godot engine as a suitable replacement for migrating Blender Game Engine users.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender Internal (known as "Blender Render"), a biased rasterization engine and scanline renderer used in previous versions of Blender, was also removed for the 2.80 release in favor of the new "EEVEE" renderer, a realtime physically based renderer.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender features an internal file system that can pack multiple scenes into a single ".blend" file.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] A wide variety of import/export scripts that extend Blender capabilities (accessing the object data via an internal API) make it possible to interoperate with other 3D tools.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender organizes data as various kinds of "data blocks" (akin to glTF), such as Objects, Meshes, Lamps, Scenes, Materials, Images, and so on.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] An object in Blender consists of multiple data blocks – for example, what the user would describe as a polygon mesh consists of at least an Object and a Mesh data block, and usually also a Material and many more, linked together.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] This allows various data blocks to refer to each other.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] There may be, for example, multiple Objects that refer to the same Mesh, and making subsequent editing of the shared mesh results in shape changes in all Objects using this Mesh.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Objects, meshes, materials, textures, etc. can also be linked to other .blend files, which is what allows the use of .blend files as reusable resource libraries.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Most of the commands are accessible via hotkeys.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] There are also comprehensive graphical menus.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Numeric buttons can be "dragged" to change their value directly without the need to aim at a particular widget, as well as being set using the keyboard.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Both sliders and number buttons can be constrained to various step sizes with modifiers like the Ctrl and Shift keys.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Python expressions can also be typed directly into number entry fields, allowing mathematical expressions to specify values.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender includes many modes for interacting with objects, the two primary ones being *Object Mode* and *Edit Mode*, which are toggled with the Tab key.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Object mode is used to manipulate individual objects as a unit, while Edit mode is used to manipulate the actual object data.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] For example, an Object Mode can be used to move, scale, and rotate entire polygon meshes, and Edit Mode can be used to manipulate the individual vertices of a single mesh.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] There are also several other modes, such as Vertex Paint, Weight Paint, and Sculpt Mode.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The Blender GUI builds its tiled windowing system on top of one or multiple windows provided by the underlying platform.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] One platform window (often sized to fill the screen) is divided into sections and subsections that can be of any type of Blender's views or window types.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The user can define multiple layouts of such Blender windows, called screens, and switch quickly between them by selecting from a menu or with keyboard shortcuts.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Each window type's own GUI elements can be controlled with the same tools that manipulate the 3D view.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] For example, one can zoom in and out of GUI-buttons using similar controls, one zooms in and out in the 3D viewport.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The GUI viewport and screen layout are fully user-customizable.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It is possible to set up the interface for specific tasks such as video editing or UV mapping or texturing by hiding features not used for the task.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Since the opening of the source code, Blender has experienced significant refactoring of the initial codebase and major additions to its feature set.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Part of this development was fostered by Google's Summer of Code program, in which the Blender Foundation has participated since 2005.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Historically, Blender has used Phabricator to manage its development but due to the announcement in 2021 that Phabricator would be discontinued, the Blender Institute began work on migrating to another system in early 2022.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] After extensive debate on what software it should choose it was finally decided to migrate to Gitea.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The migration from Phabricator to Gitea is currently a work in progress.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Development on an iPad Pro version of the application began in July 2025.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender Internal renderer has been removed from 2.8.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] *Code Quest* was a project started in April 2018 set in Amsterdam, at the Blender Institute.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The goal of the project was to get a large development team working in one place, in order to speed up the development of Blender 2.8.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] By June 29, 2018, the Code Quest project ended, and on July 2, the alpha version was completed.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Beta testing commenced on November 29, 2018, and was anticipated to take until July 2019.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender 2.80 was released on July 30, 2019.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] On April 23, 2021, the Blender Foundation announced the Cycles X project, where they improved the Cycles architecture for future development.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Key changes included a new kernel, removal of default tiled rendering (replaced by progressive refine), removal of branched path tracing, and the removal of OpenCL support.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Volumetric rendering was also replaced with better algorithms.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Cycles X has replaced the old Cycles render engine in Blender 3.0.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It is known as just "Cycles", and offers a 2x - 8x performance improvement over previous versions.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] In July 24, 2025, the Blender Foundation announced the development of a native version of Blender for the iPad, initially targeting the iPad Pro with Apple Pencil support.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The project builds on the standard Blender codebase but introduces a redesigned user interface optimized for multi-touch and stylus input, including contextual menus, floating panels, and gesture-based controls.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The first release is expected to prioritize sculpting and object manipulation, with later updates planned to add support for Grease Pencil, animation, and storyboarding tools.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] A live technology preview of Blender for iPad is scheduled for SIGGRAPH 2025 in Los Angeles, followed by further design workshops at the Blender Conference in September 2025.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Distribution details have not yet been finalized, in part due to licensing considerations involving Blender's GPL license and Apple's App Store policies.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] An Android version is also planned for future development, following the iPad release.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender is extensively documented on its website.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] There are also a number of online communities dedicated to support, such as the Blender Stack Exchange.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Due to Blender's open-source nature, other programs have tried to take advantage of its success by repackaging and selling cosmetically modified versions of it.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Examples include Bforartists, Goo Engine, Tornavis (formerly Mechanical Blender), UPBGE and Fluid Designer, which were being recognized as Blender-based.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] There were commercially made modifications of Blender such as IllusionMage, 3DMagix and 3DMofun that were sold on Chinese markets.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] However, it was found that these products did not disclose Blender's open-source license, and removed credits to Blender.As of December 2025, domain names associated with IllusionMage and 3DMagix are parked.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender started as an in-house tool for NeoGeo, a Dutch commercial animation company.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The first large professional project that used Blender was *Spider-Man 2*, where it was primarily used to create animatics and pre-visualizations for the storyboard department.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The French-language film *Friday or Another Day* (*Vendredi ou un autre jour*) was the first 35 mm feature film to use Blender for all the special effects, made on Linux workstations.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It won a prize at the Locarno International Film Festival.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The special effects were by Digital Graphics of Belgium.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Tomm Moore's *The Secret of Kells*, which was partly produced in Blender by the Belgian studio Digital Graphics, has been nominated for an Oscar in the category "Best Animated Feature Film".
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender has also been used for shows on the History Channel, alongside many other professional 3D graphics programs.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Special effects for episode 6 of *Red Dwarf* season X, screened in 2012, were created using Blender as confirmed by Ben Simonds of Gecko Animation.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Some promotional artwork for *Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS and Wii U* was partially created using Blender.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The alternative hip-hop group Death Grips has used Blender to produce music videos.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] A screenshot from the program is briefly visible in the music video for *Inanimate Sensation*.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The visual effects for the TV series *The Man in the High Castle* were done in Blender, with some of the particle simulations relegated to Houdini.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] NASA used Blender to develop the interactive web application Experience Curiosity to celebrate the 3rd anniversary of the *Curiosity* rover landing on Mars.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] This app makes it possible to operate the rover, control its cameras and the robotic arm and reproduces some of the prominent events of the Mars Science Laboratory mission.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The application was presented at the beginning of the WebGL section on SIGGRAPH 2015.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender is also used by NASA for many publicly available 3D models.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Many 3D models on NASA's 3D resources page are in a native .blend format.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The 2015 animated short film *Alike* was developed using the operating system Linux and using Blender as primary tool for modeling, animation, rendering, composing and editing.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender was used for both CGI and compositing for the movie *Hardcore Henry*.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The visual effects in the feature film *Sabogal* were done in Blender.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] VFX supervisor Bill Westenhofer used Blender to create the character "Murloc" in the 2016 film *Warcraft*.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Sandberg used Blender for multiple shots in *Lights Out*, and *Annabelle: Creation*.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender was used for parts of the credit sequences in *Wonder Woman*.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender was used for doing the animation in the film *Cinderella the Cat*.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] VFX Artist Ian Hubert used Blender for the science fiction film *Prospect*.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The 2018 film *Next Gen* was fully created in Blender by Tangent Animation.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] A team of developers worked on improving Blender for internal use, but it is planned to eventually add those improvements to the official Blender build.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The 2019 film *I Lost My Body* was largely animated using Blender's Grease Pencil tool by drawing over CGI animation allowing for a real sense of camera movement that is harder to achieve in purely traditionally drawn animation.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Ubisoft Animation Studio was reported to be planning to use Blender to replace its internal content creation software starting in 2020.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Khara and its child company Project Studio Q are trying to replace their main tool, 3ds Max, with Blender.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] They started "field verification" of Blender during their ongoing production of *Evangelion: 3.0+1.0*.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] They also signed up as Corporate Silver and Bronze members of Development Fund.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The 2020 film *Wolfwalkers* was partially created using Blender.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The 2021 Netflix production *Maya and the Three* was created using Blender.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] In 2021 SPA Studios started hiring Blender artists and as of 2022, contributes to Blender Development.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Animation started hiring Blender artists in 2022.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] VFX company Makuta VFX used Blender for the VFX for Indian blockbuster *RRR*.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender was used in several cases for the 2023 film *Spider-Man: Across the Spider-Verse*.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Sony Pictures Imageworks, the primary studio behind the film's animation, used Blender's Grease Pencil for adding line-work and 2D FX animation alongside 3D models.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Canadian animator Preston Mutanga used Blender to create the Lego-style sequence in the film.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The 2024 Latvian film *Flow* (*Straume*) was made entirely in Blender using the EEVEE render engine.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It received two nominations at the 97th Academy Awards, winning for Best Animated Feature.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Due to its free and open source nature, Blender has become the primary software of introductory 3D art, animation, visualization, and 3D printing courses at institutions including the University of Michigan, Ann Arbor where it has been made widely available in campus laboratories.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender has also been used to generate synthetic images for computer vision and AI training from crop monitoring to additive manufacturing.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Since 2005, every one to two years the Blender Foundation has announced a new creative project to help drive innovation in Blender.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The **Blender Studio** platform, launched in March 2014 as Blender Cloud, is a subscription-based cloud computing platform where members can access Blender add-ons, courses and to keep track of the production of Blender Studio's open movies.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It is currently operated by the Blender Studio, formerly a part of the Blender Institute.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It was launched to promote and fundraiser for *Project: Gooseberry*, and is intended to replace the selling of DVDs by the Blender Foundation with a subscription-based model for file hosting, asset sharing and collaboration.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender Add-ons included in Blender Studio are CloudRig, Blender Kitsu, Contact sheet Add-on, Blender Purge and Shot Builder.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] It was rebranded from Blender Cloud to Blender Studio on 22 October 2021.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The Blender Development Fund is a subscription where individuals and companies can fund Blender's development.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Corporate members include Epic Games, Nvidia, Microsoft, Apple, Unity, Intel, Decentraland, Amazon Web Services, Meta, AMD, Adobe and many more.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Individual users can also provide one-time donations to Blender via payment card, PayPal, wire transfer, and some cryptocurrencies.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The **Blender ID** is a unified login for Blender software and service users, providing a login for Blender Studio, the Blender Store, the Blender Conference, Blender Network, Blender Development Fund, and the Blender Foundation Certified Trainer Program.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The **Blender Open Data** is a platform to collect, display, and query benchmark data produced by the Blender community with related **Blender Benchmark** software.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] The Blender Network was an online platform to enable online professionals to conduct business with Blender and provide online support.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] In 2025, a beta version was put online again.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] A store to buy Blender merchandise, such as shirts, socks, beanies, etc.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Blender Extensions acts as the main repo for extensions, introduced in Blender 4.2, which include both addons and themes.
[src:blender-3d/blender-software] Users can then install and update extensions right in Blender itself.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] The geometry used in digital sculpting programs to represent the model can vary; each offers different benefits and limitations.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] The majority of digital sculpting tools on the market use mesh-based geometry, in which an object is represented by an interconnected surface mesh of polygons that can be pushed and pulled around.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] This is somewhat similar to the physical process of beating copper plates to sculpt a scene in relief.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] Other digital sculpting tools use voxel-based geometry, in which the volume of the object is the basic element.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] Material can be added and removed, much like sculpting in clay.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] Still other tools make use of more than one basic geometry representation.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] A benefit of mesh-based programs is that they support sculpting at multiple resolutions on a single model.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] Areas of the model that are finely detailed can have very small polygons while other areas can have larger polygons.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] In many mesh-based programs, the mesh can be edited at different levels of detail, and the changes at one level will propagate to higher and lower levels of model detail.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] A limitation of mesh-based sculpting is the fixed topology of the mesh; the specific arrangement of the polygons can limit the ways in which detail can be added or manipulated.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] A benefit of voxel-based sculpting is that voxels allow complete freedom over form.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] The topology of a model can be altered continually during the sculpting process as material is added and subtracted, which frees the sculptor from considering the layout of polygons on the model's surface.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] After sculpting, it may be necessary to retopologize the model to obtain a clean mesh for use in animation or real-time rendering.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] Voxels, however, are more limited in handling multiple levels of detail.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] Unlike mesh-based modeling, broad changes made to voxels at a low level of detail may completely destroy finer details.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] Sculpting can often introduce details to meshes that would otherwise have been difficult or impossible to create using traditional 3D modeling techniques.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] This makes it preferable for achieving photorealistic and hyperrealistic results, though, many stylized results are achieved as well.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] Sculpting is primarily used in high poly organic modeling (the creation of 3D models which consist mainly of curves or irregular surfaces, as opposed to hard surface modeling).
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] It is also used by auto manufacturers in their design of new cars.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] It can create the source meshes for low poly game models used in video games.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] In conjunction with other 3D modeling and texturing techniques and Displacement and Normal mapping, it can greatly enhance the appearance of game meshes often to the point of photorealism.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] Some sculpting programs like 3D-Coat, Zbrush, and Mudbox offer ways to integrate their workflows with traditional 3D modeling and rendering programs.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] Conversely, 3D modeling applications like 3ds Max, Maya and MODO are now incorporating sculpting capability as well, though these are usually less advanced than tools found in sculpting-specific applications.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] High poly sculpts are also extensively used in CG artwork for movies, industrial design, art, photorealistic illustrations, and for prototyping in 3D printing.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] Sculptors and digital artists use digital sculpting to create a model (or Digital Twin) to be materialized through CNC technologies including 3D printing.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] The final sculptures are often called Digital Sculpture or 3D printed art.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] While digital technologies have emerged in many art disciplines (painting, photography), this is less the case for digital sculpture due to the higher complexity and technology limitations to produce the final sculpture.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] The best way to learn sculpture is by understanding primary, secondary and tertiary forms.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] First, break down the object you want to make down its basic shapes, such as a sphere or cube.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] Focus on making the large, overall shape of the object.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] After that, work on the bigger shapes on top of or inside the object.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] Then, do a final detail pass, such as pores or lines to break up the shape.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] There are a number of digital sculpting tools available.
[src:blender-3d/digital-sculpting] Traditional 3D modeling suites are also beginning to include sculpting capability.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] A **point cloud** is a discrete set of data points in space.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] The points may represent a 3D shape or object.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] Each point position has its set of Cartesian coordinates (X, Y, Z).
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] Points may contain data other than position such as RGB colors, normals, timestamps and others.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] Point clouds are generally produced by 3D scanners or by photogrammetry software, which measure many points on the external surfaces of objects around them.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] When scanning a scene in real world using Lidar, the captured point clouds contain snippets of the scene, which requires alignment to generate a full map of the scanned environment.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] Point clouds are often aligned with 3D models or with other point clouds, a process termed point set registration.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] The Iterative closest point (ICP) algorithm can be used to align two point clouds that have an overlap between them, and are separated by a rigid transform.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] Point clouds with elastic transforms can also be aligned by using a non-rigid variant of the ICP (NICP).
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] With advancements in machine learning in recent years, point cloud registration may also be done using end-to-end neural networks.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] For industrial metrology or inspection using industrial computed tomography, the point cloud of a manufactured part can be aligned to an existing model and compared to check for differences.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] Geometric dimensions and tolerances can also be extracted directly from the point cloud.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] While point clouds can be directly rendered and inspected, point clouds are often converted to polygon mesh or triangle mesh models, non-uniform rational B-spline (NURBS) surface models, or CAD models through a process commonly referred to as surface reconstruction.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] There are many techniques for converting a point cloud to a 3D surface.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] In geographic information systems, point clouds are one of the sources used to make digital elevation model of the terrain.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] They are also used to generate 3D models of urban environments.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] Drones are often used to collect a series of RGB images which can be later processed on a computer vision algorithm platform such as on AgiSoft Photoscan, Pix4D, DroneDeploy or Hammer Missions to create RGB point clouds from where distances and volumetric estimations can be made.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] Point clouds can also be used to represent volumetric data, as is sometimes done in medical imaging.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] Using point clouds, multi-sampling and data compression can be achieved.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] MPEG began standardizing point cloud compression (PCC) with a Call for Proposal (CfP) in 2017.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] Three categories of point clouds were identified: category 1 for static point clouds, category 2 for dynamic point clouds, and category 3 for Lidar sequences (dynamically acquired point clouds).
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] Two technologies were finally defined: G-PCC (Geometry-based PCC, ISO/IEC 23090 part 9) for category 1 and category 3; and V-PCC (Video-based PCC, ISO/IEC 23090 part 5) for category 2.
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] The first test models were developed in October 2017, one for G-PCC (TMC13) and another one for V-PCC (TMC2).
[src:blender-3d/point-cloud] Since then, the two test models have evolved through technical contributions and collaboration, and the first version of the PCC standard specifications was expected to be finalized in 2020 as part of the ISO/IEC 23090 series on the coded representation of immersive media content.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] UV texturing permits polygons that make up a 3D object to be painted with color (and other surface attributes) from an ordinary image.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] The UV mapping process involves assigning pixels in the image to surface mappings on the polygon, usually done by "programmatically" copying a triangular piece of the image map and pasting it onto a triangle on the object.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] UV texturing is an alternative to projection mapping (e.g., using any pair of the model's X, Y, Z coordinates or any transformation of the position); it only maps into a texture space rather than into the geometric space of the object.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] The rendering computation uses the UV texture coordinates to determine how to paint the three-dimensional surface.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] In the example image, a sphere is given a checkered texture in two ways.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] On the left, without UV mapping, the sphere is carved out of three-dimensional checkers tiling Euclidean space.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] With UV mapping, the checkers tile the two-dimensional UV space, and points on the sphere map to this space according to their latitude and longitude.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] When a model is created as a polygon mesh using a 3D modeller, UV coordinates (also known as texture coordinates) can be generated for each vertex in the mesh.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] One way is for the 3D modeller to unfold the triangle mesh at the seams, automatically laying out the triangles on a flat page.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] If the mesh is a UV sphere, for example, the modeller might transform it into an equirectangular projection.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] Once the model is unwrapped, the artist can paint a texture on each triangle individually, using the unwrapped mesh as a template.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] When the scene is rendered, each triangle will map to the appropriate texture from the "decal sheet".
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] A UV map can either be generated automatically by the software application, made manually by the artist, or some combination of both.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] Often a UV map will be generated, and then the artist will adjust and optimize it to minimize seams and overlaps.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] If the model is symmetric, the artist might overlap opposite triangles to allow painting both sides simultaneously.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] UV coordinates are optionally applied per face.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] This means a shared spatial vertex position can have different UV coordinates for each of its triangles, so adjacent triangles can be cut apart and positioned on different areas of the texture map.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] The UV mapping process at its simplest requires three steps: unwrapping the mesh, creating the texture, and applying the texture to a respective face of polygon.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] UV mapping may use repeating textures, or an injective 'unique' mapping as a prerequisite for baking.
[src:blender-3d/uv-mapping] For any point P on the sphere, calculate ${\hat {d}}$ , that being the unit vector from P to the sphere's origin.
